1. /bin
• Contains essential user binary executables.
• Used by all normal users.
• Examples: cp, mv, rm, nano, nice, netstat

2. /sbin
• Contains system binary executables used for system administration.
• Usually accessed by the superuser (root).
• Examples: init, shutdown, reboot, adduser, addgroup, arp, arp-scan

3. /root
• The home directory of the root user, who is the system administrator.

4. /etc
• Stores system-wide configuration files.
• Includes network settings, user information, and system configurations.

5. /tmp
• Used to store temporary files.
• Files are usually deleted when the system is restarted.

6. /home
• Contains home directories for regular users.
• Each user has a personal directory named after their username.
• Example: /home/sai stores personal files for the user sai.

7. /boot
• Contains files required to boot the operating system, such as the kernel and bootloader files.

8. /media
• Used for mounting removable media such as USB drives, DVDs, CDs, and external hard disks.
• Devices are mounted in subdirectories named after the device.

9. /mnt
• A temporary mount point for manually mounted file systems.

10. /opt
• Used for installing optional or third-party software not managed by default package managers like apt or yum.

11. /lib
• Contains shared library files needed by the system and programs in /bin and /sbin.
